"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760720","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>The information on appeals is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost through the examination of individual case files.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on appeals that have been determined by HM Courts and Tribunals Service are published quarterly. The most recent edition (Tribunals and gender recognitions certificates statistics quarterly: January to March 2017 and 2016 to 2017) is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognitions-certificates-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2017-and-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognitions-certificates-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2017-and-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:10:00.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760720/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760720/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refusals of indefinite leave to remain were overturned on appeal between March 2016 and March 2017; how many of these appeals were not challenged by her Department; how many of those cases have been processed; and how many of those cases have been processed where her Department offered no challenge.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","105140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760721","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Home Office does not hold centrally information on the number of arrests made at the shale gas exploration site off the A583 Preston New Road.</p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes data on the number of arrests broken down by police force area. These data cannot be broken down to identify those arrested at specific locations or in relation to specific incidents.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","105151 ; 105334","2017-10-09T09:06:40.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760721/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760721/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Fracking: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many protesters arrested at the shale gas exploration site off the A583 Preston New Road during 2017 were (a) permanently resident in Lancashire, (b) resident at a protester camp and (c) permanently resident outside of Lancashire.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","105150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760722","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Home Office does not hold centrally information on the number of arrests made at the shale gas exploration site off the A583 Preston New Road.</p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes data on the number of arrests broken down by police force area. These data cannot be broken down to identify those arrested at specific locations or in relation to specific incidents.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","105150 ; 105334","2017-10-09T09:06:41.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760722/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760722/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Police: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost to Lancashire Police has been for operations in relation to the activities of protesters at the shale gas exploration site off the A583 Preston New Road in 2017.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","105151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760724","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>UK Visas and Immigration in–country contact centres provide information about the Immigration Rules and the Points Based System requirements via a number of published customer enquiry line numbers. In 2014, in line with Cabinet Office guidance , UKVI changed all 0845 and 0870 prefix helpline numbers to lower call tariff rate 0300 prefix numbers. UKVI do not generate any income from these non-geographic numbers enquiry lines.</p><p> </p><p>For overseas customers, UK Visas and Immigration have a chargeable call rates of £1.37 per minute this charge is levied to fund the commercial contract as the UK government believes it is right that those who use and benefit directly from the UK immigration system make an appropriate contribution towards meeting the costs of the immigration system. Those who use the services from outside the UK are predominantly prospective customers and in many cases no application will be made and no application fee collected.</p><p> </p><p>Our web site <a href="http://www.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a> is the main source of information and advice and is free of charge.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T10:00:19.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760724/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760724/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","UK Border Agency: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate the Government has made of the amount which accrues to the public purse of telephone calls made to the UK Border Agency.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760725","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>Information on the total number of Tier 5 (Creative and Sporting) and Visitor visa applications and grants is published quarterly.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent information can be found in the Home Office publication ‘Immigration Statistics, April – June 2017’. A breakdown of Tier 5 – Creative and Sporting visa grants by nationality is published in Visas data tables volume 2, table vi_06_q_w and Visitor visa grants by nationality is published in Visas data tables volume 3, table vi_06_q_o , available from <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/list-of-tables#visas</a>.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","105101 ; 105102 ; 105103","2017-10-10T09:22:22.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760725/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760725/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Migrant Workers: Arts and Sports Competitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of (b) Tier 5 (Temporary Work Visas - Creative and Sporting) were granted to applicants of each country in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","105106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760726","Home Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>UKVI’s published timescale for processing standard visa applications is 12 weeks (60 working days) for straightforward settlement applications, and three weeks (15 working days) for straightforward non-settlement applications.</p><p>If an application is not straightforward and expected to take longer than the standard processing timescale, UKVI will write to the customer within the standard processing time and explain what will happen next.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-10T09:18:39.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760726/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760726/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what targets are in place for the production of (a) visitor and (b) Tier 5 (Temporary Work) visas to be granted from overseas visa application centres; and whether such targets differ by country of application.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","105104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760727","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 introduced a robust regulatory regime for the metal recycling industry, including a ban on cash payments for scrap metal.</p><p>It is the responsibility of the police and local authorities to ensure that those who trade in scrap metal are compliant with the provisions of the Act including in relation to cash payments, and that action is taken against those rogue dealers who flout the law. We have undertaken a review of the Scrap Metal Dealers Act and will publish a report with our findings shortly.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-09T16:27:07.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760727/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760727/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Metals: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the enforcement of rules to prevent metal recycling operators from making cash payments for scrap metal.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760728","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>We recognise the harmful impact that metal thefts can have on victims and wider communities including through interfering with strategic frameworks and heritage sites. The Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 has helped to reduce levels of metal thefts since its introduction and we will continue to work with the police and other partners through the National Metal Theft Working Group to monitor the operation and impact of the legislation.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-09T16:25:46.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760728/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760728/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Metals: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to prevent metal thefts from (a) communications and transport networks and (b) heritage sites.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760729","Home Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>My Chief Scientific Adviser, Prof. John Aston, ensures that departmental policies are informed by the best science and engineering evidence and advice by offering independent advice directly to ministers and officials and working together with the cross Government Chief Scientific Advisers’ network to advise on issues that cut across government.</p><p> </p><p>Independent Scientific Advice is also available from many other sources including independent scientific advisory committees, the Home Office Science Advisory Council, by officials engaging directly with relevant industry and academic experts and by external commissioning of research and analysis.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-10-09T15:54:34.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760729/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760729/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Home Office: Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that her policies are informed by independent scientific advice.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760730","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>The DFID Minister of State Rory Stewart holds the portfolio responsibility for DFID’s Science and Research. The DFID Chief Scientific Adviser has met with the Minister Stewart on 3 occasions (including all-day evidence discussion) over the last 3-months to discuss a range of science and research priorities. In addition, DFID’s Chief Scientific Adviser has also had a meeting with Lord Bates during this period</p><p>The Chief Scientific Adviser continues to provide all Ministers with regular written submissions and briefings on DFID science and research activities.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-10-09T15:32:30.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760730/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760730/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-14","Department for International Development: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many meetings (a) she and (b) Ministers of her Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in her Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760731","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-09","<p>We have no access to northern Rakhine State so cannot accurately predict humanitarian needs; triangulating numerous sources of information we assess that needs are likely to be acute for the entire population, both ethnic Rakhine and Rohingya. In addition to the 480,000 Rohingya now displaced into Bangladesh, the Government of Burma has stated it estimates a further 27,000 ethnic Rakhine are also internally displaced within Rakhine State. The UK has repeatedly called on the Burmese authorities to end violence, facilitate full humanitarian access to all communities in Rakhine State, encourage return and implement the recommendations of the August 2017 Rakhine Advisory commission report. The UK is providing an additional £30 million to meet the urgent needs in both Bangladesh and Burma of those affected by the violence.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-09T15:38:46.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760731/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760731/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-09-14","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment has been made of the trend in the humanitarian situation in Rakhine State; and what steps she is taking to support refugees fleeing violence in that area.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","105191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760732","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is investing £1.3 billion to build up to 10,000 new adult prison places. The design phase of this programme is at an early stage and it is not possible to provide an estimate at this point. Our procurement activities will follow Government guidance to ensure we take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T12:34:53.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760732/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760732/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Prisons: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the value of British steel to be used in the prisons building programme.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","105156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760733","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>The department’s Director of Analytical Services also acts in capacity as the Chief Scientific Adviser for the Ministry of Justice. The Secretary of State has met with the Director on one occasion and with Ministers on three occasions over this time period.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-18T16:14:57.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760733/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760733/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Ministry of Justice: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in his Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760734","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>We confirmed following the handing down of the Supreme Court’s judgment in the case of R (Unison) v the Lord Chancellor, that we would put in place arrangements to refund those people who had paid fees in the Employment Tribunals as soon as possible.</p><p>We will announce the detailed arrangements shortly.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T15:07:36.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760734/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760734/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to reimburse people who have paid employment tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","105070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760735","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Recruitment costs* (£) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>129,357</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016</p></td><td><p>219,450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2016</p></td><td><p>301,913</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>563,028</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2017</p></td><td><p>338,803</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2017</p></td><td><p>76,497</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2017</p></td><td><p>1,176,080</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2017</p></td><td><p>1,109,430</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2017</p></td><td><p>227,939</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2017</p></td><td><p>438,487</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2017</p></td><td><p>1,097,571</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2017</p></td><td><p>1,181,421</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Recruitment costs provided only include spend on advertising and recruitment through external suppliers and does not account for recruitment-associated costs of any HMPPS staff working on resourcing initiatives or any other miscellaneous costs of recruiting staff (this data is not readily available within centrally held records). Figures include advertising costs in respect of recruitment and various media campaigns for prison officers, probation officers and the Unlocked Graduates scheme.</p><p> </p><p>*The figure provided has been drawn from our central accounting system and although care is taken when processing data, this may be subject to the inaccuracies and input errors inherent in any large scale recording system.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T08:27:10.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760735/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760735/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Prison and Probation Service: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent by HM Prison and Probation Service on recruitment in each month since September 2016.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","105091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760736","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>When Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) were under public ownership (from 1 June 2014 to 31 January 2015), we published workforce information on a quarterly basis. The final iteration of these statistics was published on 31 December 2014 and can be found at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-rehabilitation-companies-workforce-information-report-quarter-3-2014-to-2015.</p><p>Contracts with CRCs require each CRC to ensure that it employs a sufficient level of staff, and that its workforce is competent and adequately trained. We closely monitor and robustly manage providers to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T08:26:02.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760736/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760736/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff are employed under each community rehabilitation company contract; and how many staff were employed under each contract when it began operating.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","105090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760737","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>We hold providers rigorously to account for their performance and take proportional action wherever they are falling short. Our contract management teams closely monitor and robustly manage providers to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer. However, we cannot release the exact number of Service Credits each Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) has had to pay as it is commercially sensitive information.</p><p> </p><p>Service Credits can be applied when providers do not meet the required standards. Service Credits are a payment made by the CRC back to the Government, as a means of compensating for services under the contract where the CRC fails to meet the contractual service levels expected.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T08:25:40.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760737/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760737/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many Service Credits each community rehabilitation company has had to pay in compensation for the minimum level of loss or damage as a result of a reduced provision of services.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","105085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760738","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-27","<p>We do not collect centrally information on the number of claimants in Linlithgow and East Falkirk constituency who paid a fee in the Employment Tribunals.</p><p> </p><p>We confirmed, following the handing down of the Supreme Court’s judgment in the case of R (Unison) v the Lord Chancellor, that we would put in place arrangements to refund those people who had paid fees in the Employment Tribunals as soon as possible.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-27T15:47:42.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760738/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760738/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Employment Tribunals Service: Linlithgow and East Falkirk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many employment tribunal claimants in Linlithgow and East Falkirk constituency (a) paid fees and (b) have had fees refunded since 2013; what the total sum of fees still to be so refunded to claimants is; and when he intends that refund process to be completed.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","105112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760739","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-23","<p>Personal data for Employment Tribunal cases are archived 12 months after a case is concluded. Constituency-level data are only available showing claims accepted from October 2016 to June 2017. This is consistent with the published statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number of accepted claims in the East Falkirk and Linlithgow constituency from October 2016 to June 2017.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Accepted<sup>3 </sup>Claims</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Area</p></td><td><p>Period</p></td><td><p>Singles</p></td><td><p>Multiples</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Falkirk<sup>2 </sup>and Linlithgow<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>October 2016 – June 2017</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>52</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Claims accepted prior to the introduction of fees can be found in a regional breakdown, including Scotland, at https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2017-and-2016-to-2017</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes</p><p><sup>1 </sup>Linlithgow Constituency taken as accepted claims submitted within the postcode area EH49</p><p><sup>2 </sup>East Falkirk Constituency taken as accepted claims submitted within the postcode area EH30, EH47 EH2</p><p><sup>3 </sup>Accepted claims by constituency are extracted from the live ETHOS databases. Cases from the live data bases are archived 12 months after they are concluded and as such personalised data (constituency) are no longer available. Anonymised data at venue level are exported to the Central Office of the Industrial Tribunal (COIT) database.</p><p><em>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data available. </em>The data may differ slightly to that of the published stats as this data was run on a different date.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-23T11:04:28.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760739/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760739/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Employment Tribunals Service: Linlithgow and East Falkirk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many employment tribunal claimants there were in Linlithgow and East Falkirk constituency in the year (a) before and (b) after the introduction of tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","105113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760740","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is investing £1.3 billion to build up to 10,000 new adult prison places. The design and construction of HM Prison Berwyn forms part of the overall Prison Estates Transformation Programme.</p><p> </p><p>Approximately 2500 tonnes of structural steel has been used in the construction of HMP Berwyn:</p><p> </p><p>100% of this steel has been sourced from British suppliers and manufacturers.</p><p> </p><p>Our procurement activities follow Government guidance to ensure we take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T15:05:24.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760740/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760740/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Berwyn Prison: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much and what proportion of steel used in the construction of HM Prison Berwyn was sourced from British (a) manufacturers and (b) suppliers.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","105155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760741","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>As part of the Prison Safety and Reform White Paper published in November 2016, the Government committed to an increase of 2,500 prison officers by the end of 2018. <br>Between the end of October 2016 and the end of June 2017, there has been a net increase of 800 Full Time Equivalent (FTE) Band 3 to 5 prison officers. Therefore by the end of 2018 the Government plans to increase prison officer numbers by a further (net) 1,700 FTE officers</p><p>Beyond this date recruitment requirements will depend on operational staffing requirements, future prison estate changes and any future changes to Prison Officer leaving rates.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T08:27:31.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760741/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760741/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Prison Officers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison officers his Department plans to recruit in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","105129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760742","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>Pursuant to the answer to question 8744, my Department has received sub-let income of £43,751 from the Civil Service Commissioners for Northern Ireland since 2013-14 and £20,000 from the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland since 2016-17. Both of these organisations are still sub-letting accommodation from the Northern Ireland Office.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-10T14:35:41.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760742/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760742/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-14","Northern Ireland Office: Sub-letting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8744, Northern Ireland Office: buildings, from who the sub-let income in 2016-17 was from; and for what length of time that part of his Department's estate was sub-let.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760743","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>Pursuant to my previous answer to question 7938, I can confirm that the two daily rate contracts were awarded to Mercator IT Solutions for specialist independent services to assist in the introduction of a new IT platform, and the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy (CIPFA) for specialist independent services to assist in improving financial management processes. The final contract referred to in that answer was awarded to Murcom on an hourly rate basis for specialist independent services to assist with the introduction of a new records management system.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-10T14:30:12.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760743/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760743/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-14","Northern Ireland Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7938, on Northern Ireland Office: consultants, to who and for what work the daily rate contracts were awarded; to who the other contract referred to in that Answer was awarded; what payment system was used for that other contract; and what work that other contract involved.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760744","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-10","<p>The procurement that took more than one year to complete was to award a contract to carry out the installation and maintenance of security measures under the auspices of the Northern Ireland Office's Home Protection Scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-10T14:31:18.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760744/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760744/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-14","Northern Ireland Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8763, on Northern Ireland Office: procurement, if he will provide details of the procurement that took more than one year to complete.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760745","Prime Minister","false","2017-10-13","<p>I have regular meetings with ministerial colleagues, officials and others.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-10-13T11:31:47.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760745/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760745/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-14","Prime Minister: Government Chief Scientific Adviser","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, how many meetings she has had with the Government Chief Scientific Adviser in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760746","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>A number of reports on the economic impacts of migration have been published by the Government, including the report jointly published by the Home Office and then Department for Business, Innovation and Skills in 2014 titled ‘Impacts of migration on UK native employment: an analytical review of the evidence’ which provides a comprehensive summary of the research on labour market impacts of migration.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:55:39.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760746/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760746/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-14","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to publish previously unpublished reviews, studies and reports into the effects of EU migration on UK wages and the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","105099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760747","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Scotland Office does not have its own departmental Chief Scientific Adviser. Ministers of the Department regularly meet with a wide range of officials across Whitehall on a variety of issues.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-09T14:26:44.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760747/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760747/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-14","Scotland Office: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in his Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760748","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Memorandum of Terms of Occupation template used by the Scotland Office can be found on the Office of Government Commerce website as follows:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110802155020/http:/www.ogc.gov.uk/documents/CEOA_Volume_1.pdf" target="_blank"><strong>http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110802155020/http://www.ogc.gov.uk/documents/CEOA_Volume_1.pdf</strong></a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-09T14:28:00.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760748/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760748/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-14","Scotland Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8745, on Scotland Office: buildings, if his Department will publish the Memorandum of Terms of Occupation referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760749","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>No such meetings have taken place in the last three months.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-12T11:30:29.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760749/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Department for Transport: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in his Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760750","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Network Rail embeds funding for managing biodiversity within individual projects.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T14:31:25.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760750/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Network Rail: Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding Network Rail has allocated to ensure that its projects are biodiversity net positive.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","105079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760751","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The two Government Communications Service (GCS) staff members working solely on HS2 communications are being paid on the Grade 7 pay scale, and the two vacant GCS roles will be paid on the Grade 6 and Higher Executive Officer pay scales. The two members of staff who work part-time on HS2 communications are on the Senior Executive Officer and Higher Executive Officer pay scales.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-09T14:33:59.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760751/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Government Communication Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2017 to Question 8716, on Government Communications Service: staff, what the payscales are of the two members of staff who work solely on High Speed 2 (HS2); at what payscales the two vacancies were advertised; and what the payscales are for the two members of staff who work part-time on HS2 communications.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760752","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Highways England are building projects in ways designed to minimise environmental impacts now and leave a positive legacy for the future. Individual road scheme budgets are set so that schemes can mitigate their impact on biodiversity, and seek opportunities for enhancement, while achieving value for money.</p><p>The Road Investment Strategy also includes a ring-fenced environment fund of £300 million between 2015 to 2020, which includes funds for biodiversity.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-09T14:23:38.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760752/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760752/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","Highways England: Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding Highways England has allocated to ensure that projects are biodiversity net positive.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","105093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760753","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-12","<p>Safety is a key imperative of Highways England and so the safety performance of all its roads is under continuous review. Since 2011, safety improvements have been delivered at ten locations on the A19, involving improvements to traffic signals and road markings, provision of additional road capacity to reduce congestion, and improved facilities for pedestrians and cyclists.</p><p> </p><p>The Road Investment Strategy for 2015-2020, announced three schemes on the A19 for delivery, which are expected to save at least 380 casualties over a 60-year period.</p><p> </p><p>In 2017, the Department for Transport announced a congestion relief scheme to signalise the junction of A19 and A179 at Sheraton to address an existing congestion and safety issue.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-12T12:41:47.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760753/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-14","A19: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will review road safety on the A19.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","105114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760754","Wales Office","false","2017-10-11","<p>UK Government officials meet regularly with the Welsh Government on the future opportunities for St Athan. A light infantry unit will move to St Athan following the relocation of the RAF’s No. 4 school of Technical Training, maintaining St Athan’s role as an important military and civilian site<em>.</em></p><p><em> </em></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-10-11T09:51:11.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760754/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760754/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-14","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has had discussions with the Welsh Government on the possibility of utilising the site occupied by No. 4 School of Technical Training at St. Athan in the event that school is relocated; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","105109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760755","Wales Office","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales does not have a Chief Scientific Adviser.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-10-09T12:08:48.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760755/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760755/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-14","Wales Office: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in his Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760756","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>There have been no meetings with the Chief Scientific Adviser and Ministers of his Department in the last three months.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-09T16:28:59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760756/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760756/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in his Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760757","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The number (and proportion) of suppliers holding the Cyber Essentials qualification is not recorded as a specific qualification criterion by DWP.</p><p> </p><p>The Department assures each contract on a case by case basis and applies relevant security controls pertinent to the type of services being delivered and the information assets involved. In many cases the security requirements are significantly more robust than those requested within the Cyber essentials scheme.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T17:28:43.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760757/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760757/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8045, on Department for Work and Pensions: cybercrime, how many and what proportion of firms have a Cyber Essentials qualification; and whether that qualification is a requirement for delivering work procured by his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760758","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>No representations have been received on the effect of universal credit on the current local housing allowance scheme.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T12:33:09.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760758/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760758/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has received on the effect of universal credit on the applicable rate of local housing allowance for claimants.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","105214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760759","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The table below provides a response to your question from DWP’s State Pension administrative data on the number of State Pension recipients aged over 100-years old. There are known issues with the quality of this data due to historical operational processes which mean that some cases remain on the administrative data although they are no longer in payment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>-</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Caseload</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>13,510</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>1,120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>740</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: DWP Work and Pensions Longitudinal Study, February 2017.</em></p><p><em>Caseload figures have been rounded to the nearest 10.</em></p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ul><li>There are additionally 70 persons resident in Great Britain aged over 100-years old whose location is unknown.</li><li>DWP does not administer State Pensions for Northern Ireland. The figures above relate solely to those that are administered by the DWP.</li><li>DWP have reviewed the operational process for keeping records no longer in payment on the system and improvements are underway to close down these cases.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-10-09T17:26:12.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760759/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760759/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people aged over 100-years old receive the state pension in (a) England, (b) Scotland, (c) Wales and (d) Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","105189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760760","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>DWP have contracts with 2 private sector suppliers,</p><p>Xerox (UK) Limited and Engie UK &amp; Ireland.</p><p>Xerox (UK) Limited annual contract valuation is £5 million, Engie is £13.5million.</p><p>These contacts relate to incoming &amp; onward mail processing and handling for the Authority</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T17:32:48.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760760/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760760/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Department for Work and Pensions: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7282, on Department for Work and Pensions: correspondence, how many contracts are with private sector suppliers; who those suppliers are; what the value is of each of those contracts; and what part of his Department's correspondence process those contracts relate to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is committed to increase the basic State Pension up to the full amount of the new State Pension by the Triple Lock for the duration of this Parliament. The Triple Lock ensures that the highest of the growth in wages, prices (CPI) and 2.5% is applied. A decision on the rate to be used is taken annually following the publication of price inflation and earnings growth rate statistics in October.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-10-09T12:40:37.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760761/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","State Retirement Pensions: Uprating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Government has plans to raise the basic state pension in 2018 by September 2017's CPI inflation figure of 2.9 per cent.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","105086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760762","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>As Housing Benefit is an income-related benefit, regard is normally had to all forms of income, including from self-employment, when assessing entitlement. The net profit figure used in the calculation of Housing Benefit is obtained by deducting any expenses wholly and exclusively incurred for the purpose of the employment, from the gross receipts of the business. This includes capital and interest repayments on loans used to replace existing equipment and machinery. The value of the assets of a business is disregarded when calculating a person’s capital while the business is continuing. No income is taken into account where there are no net profits.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that the current rules are working in accordance with the policy intention and there are no plans to amend them.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T12:35:29.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760762/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760762/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Housing Benefit: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will change the housing benefit criteria for small business owners so that only the owner's income is taken into account in the first year of the business making a profit.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","105145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is committed to creating a country where everyone has the chance to go as far as their talents and hard work will take them. This includes taking action that will make a meaningful difference to the lives of the most disadvantaged children and families. This requires an approach that goes beyond the safety net provided by the welfare system to tackle the root causes of child poverty and disadvantage, so that everyone has the chance to realise their potential. <br></p><p>We know that children living in workless families are significantly more disadvantaged, and achieve poorer long-term outcomes than other children, including those living in lower-income working families. And despite record levels of employment, around 1 in 8 children across the UK live in workless families. <br></p><p>We are therefore taking action to ensure that workless families who face additional, complex barriers have the support they need to help them move on with their lives. <em>Improving Lives: Helping Workless Families</em>, published on 4 April, provided a framework for a continued focus on improving children’s outcomes, now and in the future</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-09T17:35:35.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760763/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Government has made of the effect on his Department's policies of the findings of the Social Mobility Commission report, Time for change: an assessment of Government policies on social mobility 1997-2017, published on 28 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760764","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government worked closely with the exhibition organiser, Clarion Defence and Security Ltd, to ensure that all exhibitors at Defence and Security Equipment International (DSEI) were aware of their export control obligations. This includes which items they were prohibited from supplying or delivering – or agreeing to supply or deliver – or refraining from acts calculated to promote the supply or delivery of such items, including exhibiting and advertising. Government hosted a pre-event briefing with Clarion to ensure they were fully aware of their responsibilities. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), who are responsible for the enforcement of export and trade controls, also attended the briefing to provide clear compliance guidance and to review the procedures Clarion had put in place.</p><p>The Export Control Joint Unit had a dedicated stand at DSEI which was manned by Ministry of Defence, Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Department for International Trade officials. HMRC were present during each day of the exhibition to ensure exhibitors complied with UK Trade Controls, as they were in 2015. C-RICH Co and other stall holders were visited by HMRC.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","105414","2017-10-12T11:57:27.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760764/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760764/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Arms Trade: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the Government is taking steps to monitor the (a) sale and (b) promotion by companies at the Defence and Security Equipment International of (i) electric stun guns, baton type, (ii) electric stun guns, hand type, (iii) leg irons and (iv) thumb cuffs to countries to which (A) the UK and (B) international obligations prohibit the sale of (1) such and (2) military equipment.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","105098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760765","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is committed to supporting businesses to offer their customers choice about how they pay for goods and services. Payment by instalments can provide consumers with a helpful way to spread the costs of household goods and services, and this can be an important budgeting tool for consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government took action in 2015 to exempt credit that is provided free of interest and charges over less than 12 months from Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) regulation, unless 12 or more repayments are due.</p><p> </p><p>To be exempt from FCA regulation, the credit agreement must not be a conditional sale, hire purchase or pawn agreement, and must not finance the purchase of land. The credit agreement must finance the purchase of specific goods or services, must be for a fixed amount, and must contain no charges, interest or administration fees.</p><p> </p><p>The provisions within the Consumer Credit Act 1974 (CCA) to enable full payment ahead of time do not apply to agreements which fall under this exemption. The CCA provides important safeguards to protect consumers, and so the exemption is limited to agreements which meet the specified criteria. The Government has no plans to modify this exemption.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-09T13:11:10.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760765/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760765/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Hire Services: Credit Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on changes in the level of use of personal contracts for agreements in the last five years; what assessment he has made of the reasons for those changes; and if he will extend the provisions of the Consumer Credit Act 1974 to enable full payment ahead of time to personal contract hire agreements; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","105143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760766","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>As of 17<sup>th</sup> September 2017, the core Industrial Strategy Team within BEIS is led by Alexandra Jones, and employs 20 men and 18 women.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-09T16:37:44.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760766/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760766/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2017 to Question 9015, how many women work in the Industrial Strategy Team.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","105132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760767","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>The European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and the European Committee for Electrotechnical Standardization (CENELEC) are not EU bodies, although they have a special status in the EU. We are working with BSI, the UK’s national standards body and the UK member of CEN and CENELEC, to ensure that our future relationship with CEN and CENELEC continues to support a productive, open and competitive business environment in the UK and to ensure that funding provided to BSI by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy also supports this goal.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-09T16:34:54.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760767/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760767/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","British Standards Institution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what changes to the funding and responsibilities of the British Standards Institute will be made when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","105144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760768","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>I refer the honourable Member to the answer I gave her on 13 September 2017, to Question 9015:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-06/9015/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-06/9015/</a>.</p><p>We are unable to provide an answer as this information is not centrally held and could only be obtained at disproportionate costs.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-09T16:35:56.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760768/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760768/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2017 to Question 9015, how many and what proportion of (a) civil servants and (b) advisors working directly on the industrial strategy are women.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","105131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760769","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government will shortly bring forward proposals to ensure that foreign ownership of companies controlling important infrastructure does not undermine British security or essential services. These proposals will consolidate and strengthen Government’s powers to protect national security.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-10-12T11:03:52.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760769/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760769/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Infrastructure: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to ensure the delivery of (a) utilities, (b) communications, (c) transport and (d) energy infrastructure in the event of foreign ownership of such infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","105095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760770","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department is not responsible for carrying out checks on dividends paid by companies to ensure that they do not exceed their distributable reserves.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:03:14.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760770/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760770/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Companies: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what checks his Department carries out to ensure that dividends paid by companies do not exceed their distributable reserves.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760771","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government has no plans to appoint such a committee. The work of the Financial Reporting Council has been reviewed by committees in both Houses of Parliament and we would expect this to continue.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T11:05:56.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760771/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760771/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Financial Reporting Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will appoint an independent committee to examine the governance of the Financial Reporting Council.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760772","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Financial Reporting Council (FRC) agreed a disciplinary scheme with the accountancy professional bodies in 2004 meeting requirements in company law for it to have in place arrangements with the recognised supervisory bodies for the purposes of disciplining auditors. The funding basis for the scheme was that the professional bodies would fund the costs of disciplinary actions and that any costs and fines ordered against the members of their bodies would be paid to those bodies.</p><p>New statutory powers for the FRC to impose fines on auditing firms were introduced in the Statutory Auditors and Third Country Auditors Regulations 2016. The Regulations require that fines imposed under the powers must be transferred by the FRC to the Secretary of State.</p><p>The FRC continues to maintain a disciplinary scheme for non-statutory audit matters: for fines recovered under those arrangements, the fines continue to be paid over to the relevant accountancy professional bodies.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T11:04:58.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760772/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760772/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Audit: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish the dates on which his Department authorised the Financial Reporting Council to pass the fines levied on auditing firms to recognised supervisory bodies.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760773","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-13","<p>The Financial Reporting Council (FRC) oversees of the work of recognised supervisory bodies (RSBs) as the Secretary of State’s delegate and the UK’s competent authority for audit. The FRC is designated for these purposes by the Companies Act 2006 and certain secondary legislation. If the RSBs breach the requirements put in place under that legislation, the FRC can remove the bodies’ recognition and can also reclaim any audit regulatory functions that it has delegated to them.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-13T12:49:08.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760773/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760773/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will appoint an independent committee to examine the governance of recognised supervisory bodies.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760774","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-10","<p>Shareholding through nominee accounts is commonly used for legitimate investment and commercial reasons. The Government has no plans to introduce legislative proposals to prohibit nominee shareholdings.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-10T12:49:38.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760774/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760774/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Shareholders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will introduce legislative proposals to prohibit nominee shareholdings.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760775","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>Our Green Paper: Security and Sustainability in Defined Benefit Schemes looked at a number of potential measures to further protect DB schemes – including introducing a system for compulsory clearance by the Regulator for certain corporate transactions and a requirement for employers to consult with trustees before paying dividends where the scheme is underfunded.</p><p>We are currently analysing the feedback received and will publish a White Paper in winter. Any future changes to legislation need to be considered carefully against the need to ensure appropriate protections for members, the impact on business and the wider economy.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","105226","2017-10-09T17:02:25.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760775/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760775/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Companies: Mergers and Takeovers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to require companies with a deficit on their defined benefit pension scheme to seek the approval of the Pensions Regulator before agreeing to any merger or takeover.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760776","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-10","<p>Companies are already required to identify all of their shareholders. Companies Act 2006 requires companies to keep a register of members and enter the details of members in this register (in the case of a company limited by shares, the members are the shareholders). The register of members must be kept available for inspection at the company’s registered office and any person may request to inspect it on payment of any fee set by the company (the size of which is limited by legislation).</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-10T12:50:20.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760776/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760776/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760776/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Shareholders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will introduce legislative proposals to require companies to identify all of their shareholders.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760777","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>Companies House does not have powers to verify the authenticity of company directors, secretaries and registered office addresses. However, it does carry out a number of checks on all information received; ensuring it is valid, complete, correctly formatted and in compliance with company filing requirements. The obligation to ensure the information is accurate lies with the company and its directors. An offence is committed by the company if it files false information. Companies House maintains one of the most open and extensively accessed companies’ register in the world. It is a powerful tool in identifying false, inaccurate or possibly fraudulent information. With many eyes viewing the data, errors, omissions or worse can be identified and reported.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:31:31.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760777/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760777/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what procedures are used by Companies House to verify the authenticity of company directors, secretaries and registered addresses.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760778","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>No action has been taken at this time against the promoters and officers of Magnolia Fundaction UK Ltd for filing inappropriate information in Italian at Companies House. The company has already filed documents providing appropriate information and terminating the inappropriate appointment.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:25:30.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760778/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760778/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether any action has been taken against the promoters and officers of Magnolia Fundaction UK Ltd for filing information at Companies House which stated a director's name as The Chicken Thief and described his occupation as fraudster.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760779","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>None of the Recognised Professional Bodies who regulate insolvency are subject to Freedom of Information legislation.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:23:15.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760779/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760779/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Professional Organisations: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which Recognised Professional Bodies are authorised to regulate insolvency but are not subject to Freedom of Information legislation.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760780","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>The following bodies are authorised to act as Recognised Supervisory Bodies under the Companies Act 2006: The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales; Chartered Accountants Ireland; The Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland; and the Association of Chartered Certified Accountants. They are independent private bodies and are not subject to the Freedom of Information Act.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:20:46.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760780/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760780/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Financial Services: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which organisations are authorised to act as Recognised Supervisory Bodies under the Companies Act but not subject to Freedom of Information legislation.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760781","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>It would not be appropriate for details of the Insolvency Service’s ongoing investigation into BHS to be made public at this point, as that may prejudice the outcome of any criminal or civil cases which arise from it.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T14:16:55.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760781/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760781/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","British Home Stores: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress is being made on the Insolvency Service's investigation into the affairs of BHS.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760782","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-09","<p>Our Green Paper: Security and Sustainability in Defined Benefit Schemes looked at a number of potential measures to further protect DB schemes – including introducing a system for compulsory clearance by the Regulator for certain corporate transactions and a requirement for employers to consult with trustees before paying dividends where the scheme is underfunded.</p><p>We are currently analysing the feedback received and will publish a White Paper in winter. Any future changes to legislation need to be considered carefully against the need to ensure appropriate protections for members, the impact on business and the wider economy.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","105228","2017-10-09T17:02:25.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760782/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760782/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-14","Companies: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will introduce legislative proposals to prohibit companies with a deficit on their defined benefit pension scheme from paying any dividends without the prior approval of the Pensions Regulators.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760783","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>Between 14<sup>th</sup> June 2017 and 14<sup>th</sup> September 2017 the Chief Scientific Adviser for the Department for Business, Energy (BEIS) and Industrial Strategy has met with:</p><p>(a) the Secretary of State for BEIS six times in person and four times by telephone; and</p><p>(b) BEIS Ministers six times in person and once by telephone.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-09T16:11:59.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760783/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760783/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many meetings (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have had with the Chief Scientific Adviser in his Department in the last three months.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760784","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-10","<p>The Small Business Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 inserts new sections 156A-C in the Companies Act 2006 that will require that all company directors should be natural persons and prohibit (subject to exceptions) the appointment of corporate entities as directors. The Government will bring forward regulations to set out the exceptions and commence this requirement when Parliamentary time allows.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-10T12:50:51.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760784/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760784/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will introduce legislative proposals to prohibit directors of companies registered in the UK Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories from acting as directors of UK registered companies.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760785","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is strongly committed to the success of the Life Sciences in the UK and is already taking action in key areas to consolidate and build on the strength of the sector. Government welcomes the Life Sciences Industrial Strategy recently launched by Sir John Bell and will respond through a sector deal negotiation.</p><p>As part of this commitment, the Government is working hard to support businesses and entrepreneurs across the UK to ensure they can access the finance and wider support they need to grow and have the right conditions for companies to invest long-term. Through the British Business Bank (BBB) Venture Capital Catalyst Fund a £400m expansion was announced at Autumn Statement 2016, which aims to crowd in a total of £1bn for companies looking to scale up.</p><p>In addition, work is continuing through HM Treasury’s Patient Capital Review to look into long-term investment in innovative companies with life sciences featuring highly. The Department is working closely with HM Treasury and recommendations from the review will be made to my right hon. Friend the Chancellor for the Autumn Budget.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-09T16:09:12.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760785/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760785/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Life Science: Venture Capital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to increase the availability of scale-up capital for life science companies.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","105238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760786","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department for International Trade has recently concluded a recruitment campaign to appoint a Chief Scientific Adviser. The appointment will be announced in due course.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-12T11:15:21.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760786/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760786/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Department for International Trade: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what plans he has to appoint a Chief Scientific Adviser.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760787","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-10","<p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p><p>We will not be publishing assessments made of the military equipment approved for exports to Venezuela between 2015 – 2017 because such assessments are confidential.</p><p>The Government publishes Official Statistics (on a quarterly and annual basis) on export licences granted and refused on GOV.UK. These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences.</p><p>Currently this includes information up to 31 March 2017. Information covering 1 April to 30 June 2017 will be published on 17 October 2017 and information covering 1 July to 30 September 2017 will be published on 16 January 2018.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-10T09:41:11.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760787/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760787/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-14","Defence Equipment: Venezuela","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will publish the assessments made of the military equipment approved for exports to Venezuela between 2015 and 2017.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","105162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760788","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-09","<p>As is usual practice, the Government considers the implications of publishing its analysis, including, where appropriate, looking at a range of relevant factors to decide whether it would harm the Government’s negotiating position. The Government respects the role of Parliament in this process and has committed to keeping both Houses informed throughout. However, the Government also takes seriously its commitment not to publish anything that would undermine its negotiating position. Government publications are based on the principle of collective agreement, and therefore the decision to publish Government material is a collective one.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-09T16:55:53.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760788/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760788/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-14","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2017 to Question 8561, what the criteria is for deciding what information, if published, would undermine the ability of the Government to negotiate the best deal for the UK; and which Minister is responsible for making that decision.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","105087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760789","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to ensuring that we access the very best scientific expertise. We have actively considered the best way of achieving this and have appointed Chris Jones, Director for Justice Security and Migration (JSM) as Chief Scientific Adviser. We have taken the decision to appoint a Chief Scientific Advisor to ensure that departmental decisions are informed by the best science and engineering advice and to provide a route for us to engage directly with the wider network of Chief Scientific Advisers where necessary.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-10-16T16:14:56.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760789/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760789/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans he has to appoint a Chief Scientific Adviser.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","105173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760790","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government Cyber Essentials Assurance Framework provides organisations with a framework that provides a set of basic security controls for IT systems and an assurance framework that assesses against common cyber threats. It is therefore designed to allow an organisation to achieve certification and does not apply to individuals.</p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union uses capabilities provided by other Government Departments and the Memorandum of Understanding between the Department and its OGD supplier stipulates that they must adhere to HMG security practices and certification.</p><p>Any technology based procurement undertaken by the department must meet HMG policies on Cyber Security and proof is requested as part of the tender process.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-09T16:51:58.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760790/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760790/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8036, on Department for Work and Pensions: cybercrime, how many and what proportion of contractors have obtained a Government Cyber Essentials certificate; and whether such a certificate is a requirement for delivering work procured by his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760791","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department has an approvals hierarchy that ensures that all proposals for expenditure on consultancy or temporary staff are reviewed and approved by Senior Civil Servants. This ensures that there is a fully documented business justification for investment decisions which, where appropriate, results in a full business case.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-12T16:45:28.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760791/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760791/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7952, on Department for Exiting the European Union: temporary employment, how many and what proportion of requests for consultancy and temporary staff were accompanied by a formal business case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760792","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-10","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-10T14:47:29.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760792/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760792/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-14","Ministry of Defence: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8368, on Ministry of Defence: redundancy pay, how much was paid in redundancy payments to civilian personnel who are (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760793","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-11","<p>Since it was established the Department has procured consultancy services with respect to programme and project management and in relation to an options appraisal for back office shared service systems.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-10-11T16:41:13.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760793/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760793/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7931, on Department for Exiting the European Union: consultants, for what project deliverables his Department has procured consultancy services since it was established.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760794","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-09T08:23:34.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760794/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760794/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-14","Coroners: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much the UK Coroners Service spent on translation services in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","105339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760795","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department. The Civil Service constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government's commitment to leave the EU and get the best deal for the UK. Civil Service HR is working with all departments across the Civil Service to better understand their capacity and capability requirements.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-23T14:38:09.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760795/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760795/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the Civil Service workforce required to administer a transitional period when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","105337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760796","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-29","<p>The table below sets out the cost of sickness pay paid to staff in my Department each year from 1 April 2009 to 30<sup>th</sup> June 2016. Information about the cost of sickness pay paid to staff in my Department before April 2009 is not available.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2009*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016**</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Statutory Sick Pay</p></td><td><p>£269</p></td><td><p>£1,567</p></td><td><p>£5,163</p></td><td><p>£2,063</p></td><td><p>£4,903</p></td><td><p>£3,266</p></td><td><p>£6,628</p></td><td><p>£4,928</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Occupational Sick Pay</p></td><td><p>£139,535</p></td><td><p>£203,025</p></td><td><p>£528,810</p></td><td><p>£406,837</p></td><td><p>£405,908</p></td><td><p>£439,844</p></td><td><p>£465,716</p></td><td><p>£290,081</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£141,813</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£206,602</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£535,984</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£410,911</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£412,824</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£445,124</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£474,358</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£297,025</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong><sub>* From 1 Apr 2009 </sub></strong> <strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong><sub>**To 30 Jun 2016</sub></strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Information about sickness absence in the Cabinet Office is published on the Cabinet Office website at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-absence-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-absence-data</a></p><p> </p><p>The most recent published figures show that for the year to 30 June 2017, the Cabinet Office has one of the lowest recorded sickness rates across the Civil Service at 2.9 average working days lost when compared to the latest Civil Service average of 7.0 .</p><p> </p><p>My Department is committed to reducing work related absence due to mental illness and has a number of services in place to support members of staff suffering from such conditions. Our Workwell community is staffed by volunteers who aim to make Cabinet Office a happy and healthy workplace through a number of interventions including a listening service for staff. We also offer a 24 hour counselling support helpline through our Employee Assistance Programme provider and advocate early referral to our occupational health service where appropriate, for advice on a number of conditions including mental health.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-29T11:13:14.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760796/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760796/answer","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760796/answer/previousversion/13900","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Cabinet Office: Sick Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the cost of sickness pay to staff in his Department was in each of the 10 years prior to June 2016.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","105338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760797","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The two procurements that took longer to award than twelve months in 2013-14 were<br>ConsultancyOne (RM 1502) and Locum Doctors including Locum GPs (RM 1570).</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-19T11:55:20.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760797/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760797/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Crown Commercial Service: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7708, on Crown Commercial Service: procurement, what the two contracts were where the tender ran for longer than one year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760798","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Civil Service Workforce Plan 2016-2020 includes an action to pilot alternative to<br>competency-based recruitment and promotion in the Civil Service. A number of<br>departments are involved in piloting alternative approaches. These are: Department for<br>Work and Pensions; HM Revenue and Customs; Office for National Statistics; Department<br>for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs; and Department for Transport. In addition,<br>alternatives to competency-based recruitment are being trialled in some Senior Leader<br>recruitment, some apprenticeships, the Civil Service Fast Stream and Fast Track schemes<br>and some talent schemes. These pilots are ongoing, and will be evaluated and, where<br>appropriate, rolled out across the Civil Service. The outcomes will not be published.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T15:01:55.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760798/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760798/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7591, on civil servants: recruitment, which Government Departments are included in the pilots; when those pilots are expected to be completed; and whether the outcomes of those pilots will be published.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760799","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has conducted deployments of (a) staff and (b) experts to Georgia, Ukraine, Tunisia, Montenegro, Belgium (NATO), Jordan and Afghanistan.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-14T13:15:45.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760799/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760799/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Government Communication Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, to which countries the Knowledge and Capability Unit of the Government Communication Service has deployed (a) staff and (b) experts since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760800","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>The cost of each completed project in Georgia, Ukraine, Tunisia, Montenegro and NATO was £42,225, £205,512, £993,500, £74,848 and £26,260 respectively. All projects directly support UK foreign policy objectives.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-14T11:45:57.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760800/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760800/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Government Communication Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8718, on Government Communication Service, in which country the five projects were based; what the cost of each such project was; and what estimate he has made of the value of each project to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","105310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760801","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>Electoral law is clear that a person must be included in the register of electors for a<br>poll in order to be entitled to vote at that poll. The Government recognises that it is<br>possible for postal ballot papers to be issued to a postal voter who may subsequently<br>be removed from the register to be used at the poll. We will look to review the current<br>provisions on the cancellation of postal ballot papers to see whether improvements<br>can be made to the law in this area.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-19T11:00:01.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760801/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760801/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760801/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will assess the merits of introducing a process to cancel a postal ballot paper issued to an elector who is subsequently deleted from the electoral register during an election period.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","105247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760802","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Government recognises the concerns surrounding the inclusion of home addresses on electoral documents which are published and we will consider this whilst looking at issues in relation to publication of the home addresses of candidates.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-23T16:09:28.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760802/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760802/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Elections: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will remove the requirement for election agents' home addresses to be published.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","105312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760803","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Government is clear that spending by candidates at elections should continue to be transparent. We will discuss with returning officers and the Electoral Commission how processes relating to the return and publication of spending returns could be improved. The development of online reporting and inspection is likely incur substantial cost as an online platform would need to be developed, established and maintained.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-23T16:07:50.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760803/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760803/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760803/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Candidates: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will review the process of recording candidates' expenses including the consideration of the return to, and subsequent reporting of, expenses to returning officers and the possible provision of online reporting and inspection mechanisms.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","105313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760804","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Government, in its response to the Sir Eric Pickle’s review of electoral law, agreed with this recommendation. We will continue to work with the Law Commissions and other organisations such as the Electoral Commission on how best to implement the recommendations set out in their review.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-23T16:08:30.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760804/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760804/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760804/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Elections: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether he plans to introduce a formal complaints system as recommended by the Law Commission to provide for a clearer and local system of accountability and challenge.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","105314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760805","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government recognises that greater clarity could be provided on deferring<br>publication of the electoral register under these circumstances. We will keep the<br>matter under review and address it when the opportunity arises.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-19T10:51:09.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760805/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760805/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760805/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will assess the merits of clarifying the arrangements around deferring publication of the electoral register where an election occurs during the defined canvass period.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","105248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760806","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>It is not unusual for the Cabinet Secretary and Head of the Civil Service to comment<br>publicly on matters relating to the management of the Civil Service. Information relating to<br>internal discussion and advice is not disclosed.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-10-19T09:00:00.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760806/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760806/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760806/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Minister authorised the Cabinet Secretary to discuss the comments made by Lord Maude on the UK leaving the EU with the media.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","105381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760807","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-15","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department. The Civil Service constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government's commitment to leave the EU and get the best deal for the UK. Civil Service HR is working with all departments across the Civil Service to better understand their capacity and capability requirements.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-15T15:17:30.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760807/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760807/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760807/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-14","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many full-time equivalent civil servants have been assigned work on the UK leaving the EU in the last 12 months; and what estimate he has made of the cost of that work.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","105335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760809","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-10","<p>There are 25 Anti-Money Laundering (AML) supervisors in the UK. These include the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), HM Revenue and Customs, the Gambling Commission and the 22 accountancy and legal professional bodies listed below:</p><p> </p><ol><li>Association of Accounting Technicians</li><li>Association of Chartered Certified Accountants</li><li>Association of International Accountants</li><li>Association of Taxation Technicians</li><li>Chartered Institute of Legal Executives</li><li>Chartered Institute of Management Accountants</li><li>Chartered Institute of Taxation</li><li>Council for Licensed Conveyancers</li><li>Faculty of Advocates</li><li>Faculty Office of the Archbishop of Canterbury</li><li>General Council of the Bar</li><li>General Council of the Bar of Northern Ireland</li><li>Insolvency Practitioners Association</li><li>Institute of Certified Bookkeepers</li><li>Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales</li><li>Institute of Chartered Accountants in Ireland</li><li>Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland</li><li>Institute of Financial Accountants</li><li>International Association of Bookkeepers</li><li>Law Society</li><li>Law Society of Northern Ireland</li><li>Law Society of Scotland</li></ol><p> </p><p>These supervisors monitor and enforce compliance with AML legislation. This complements the work of law enforcement agencies, including the National Crime Agency, the Serious Fraud Office and local police forces.</p><p> </p><p>The government has reviewed the supervisory regime and is implementing reforms to strengthen it. These include creating a new team – the Office for Professional Body AML Supervision (OPBAS) – within the FCA to help, and ensure, professional bodies provide consistently high standards of supervision. OPBAS will also work across the regime, to facilitate high standards amongst statutory supervisors and strengthen supervisors’ collaboration with law enforcement.</p><p> </p><p>Law enforcement agencies, the FCA, HM Revenue and Customs and the Gambling Commission are subject to the Freedom of Information Act whilst the 22 professional bodies named above are not. The government supports greater transparency to help build public confidence in our regime, and the 2017 Money Laundering Regulations require that all AML supervisors, including the 22 professional bodies, provide information to inform the Treasury’s Annual Supervision Report.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","105356","2017-10-10T12:53:49.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760809/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760809/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760809/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which organisations responsible for monitoring and enforcing anti-money laundering laws are not subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760810","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-10","<p>There are 25 Anti-Money Laundering (AML) supervisors in the UK. These include the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), HM Revenue and Customs, the Gambling Commission and the 22 accountancy and legal professional bodies listed below:</p><p> </p><ol><li>Association of Accounting Technicians</li><li>Association of Chartered Certified Accountants</li><li>Association of International Accountants</li><li>Association of Taxation Technicians</li><li>Chartered Institute of Legal Executives</li><li>Chartered Institute of Management Accountants</li><li>Chartered Institute of Taxation</li><li>Council for Licensed Conveyancers</li><li>Faculty of Advocates</li><li>Faculty Office of the Archbishop of Canterbury</li><li>General Council of the Bar</li><li>General Council of the Bar of Northern Ireland</li><li>Insolvency Practitioners Association</li><li>Institute of Certified Bookkeepers</li><li>Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales</li><li>Institute of Chartered Accountants in Ireland</li><li>Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland</li><li>Institute of Financial Accountants</li><li>International Association of Bookkeepers</li><li>Law Society</li><li>Law Society of Northern Ireland</li><li>Law Society of Scotland</li></ol><p> </p><p>These supervisors monitor and enforce compliance with AML legislation. This complements the work of law enforcement agencies, including the National Crime Agency, the Serious Fraud Office and local police forces.</p><p> </p><p>The government has reviewed the supervisory regime and is implementing reforms to strengthen it. These include creating a new team – the Office for Professional Body AML Supervision (OPBAS) – within the FCA to help, and ensure, professional bodies provide consistently high standards of supervision. OPBAS will also work across the regime, to facilitate high standards amongst statutory supervisors and strengthen supervisors’ collaboration with law enforcement.</p><p> </p><p>Law enforcement agencies, the FCA, HM Revenue and Customs and the Gambling Commission are subject to the Freedom of Information Act whilst the 22 professional bodies named above are not. The government supports greater transparency to help build public confidence in our regime, and the 2017 Money Laundering Regulations require that all AML supervisors, including the 22 professional bodies, provide information to inform the Treasury’s Annual Supervision Report.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","105355","2017-10-10T12:53:49.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760810/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760810/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760810/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what organisations are responsible for monitoring and enforcing anti-money laundering laws.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760811","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 19<sup>th</sup> September 2017 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-09-12/10031" target="_blank">10031</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-12T11:01:58.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760811/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760811/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760811/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-14","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to empower local authorities to tackle non-compliance with the National Minimum Wage.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","105293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760812","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Details about the annual property costs of the HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) new regional centre in Leeds is commercially sensitive information; disclosing it could compromise the negotiations currently in progress on other regional centres and government hubs.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T15:03:00.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760812/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760812/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760812/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Revenue and Customs: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 6755, on HM Revenue and Customs: Yorkshire and the Humber, what estimate he has made of the annual property costs of the new regional hub recently announced for Leeds.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","105357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760813","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>A number of HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) officers across various compliance, legal, technical and policy teams can be involved in a case at any given time. HMRC officers may work on multiple cases, involving several different behaviours and risks at any one time. Therefore it is not possible to calculate the entire cost to HMRC of this particular investigation.</p><p> </p><p>As this case was not in the costs regime, HMRC did not apply for its costs.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T15:11:29.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760813/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760813/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Stagecoach Group: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse has been of the case of Stagecoach Group PLC and Stagecoach Holdings Limited and the Commissioners for Her Majesty; and how much of that cost has been recovered.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760814","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>Since the last update to Parliament in November 2016, HMRC has tripled the number of criminal and civil investigations linked to the Panama papers.</p><p> </p><p>To date, the work of the Panama Papers Taskforce has led to civil and criminal investigations into 66 individuals for suspected tax evasion, including high net worth individuals. As part of this HMRC has made four arrests; and carried out six interviews under caution.</p><p> </p><p>Taskforce partners have made three arrests in relation to an organised crime group suspected of a £125m conspiracy to defraud pension investors, tax evasion and associated money laundering. They have also identified leads relevant to a major insider trading operation, in relation to which a number of individuals have been arrested and are on bail pending further activity.</p><p> </p><p>UK law enforcement continues to interrogate and exploit Panama Papers related data, identifying previously unknown individuals, companies and properties, making links between them and providing intelligence and investigative opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>The systems used to launder money and evade tax through offshore structures are complex and highly sophisticated. The Joint Financial Analysis Centre and HMRC’s expert analysts are using leading-edge technology to unpick these structures and trace them back to individuals. This work is painstaking and forensic and there are no easy shortcuts.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is not a prosecuting authority. Its focus is on building the strongest possible cases in order to secure convictions, and it expects to refer cases to the prosecuting authorities from autumn 2017 onwards.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-12T16:11:13.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760814/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760814/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress his Department has made in its inquiry into the Panama Papers.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760815","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The EU PANA Committee’s mission to the UK took place on 9 and 10 February 2017 and representatives from the UK government were invited to update the Committee on the UK’s progress in tackling money laundering, tax evasion and tax avoidance. As the proceedings were primarily concerned with the UK’s operational response, witnesses from the government’s Panama Papers Taskforce, including HMRC, the Financial Conduct Authority and the National Crime Agency, gave evidence during the allotted 90-minute evidence session. HM Treasury Ministers were not present.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-12T16:08:57.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760815/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760815/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","EP Committee of Inquiry into Money Laundering, Tax Avoidance and Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what dates he has met the EU PANA Committee; what was the duration of each of those meetings; and what topics were discussed at each.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760816","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The cost of the litigation will not be known until the parties have agreed on the amounts to be paid under a costs order made by the Court of Appeal. If the parties cannot agree, the Court will assess the amounts. The costs order does not apply to Ernst &amp; Young which was not a party to the litigation.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T15:21:49.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760816/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760816/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Greene King: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what was the cost of litigation in the case of Greene King Plc & Anor v HM Revenue and Customs; and how much of this has been recovered from Ernst & Young.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760817","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>Since 2010, 9705 people in England and Wales have been successfully convicted for money laundering offences – most of these are under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 which provides for various money laundering offences, including where an individual knows or suspects they may be facilitating money laundering or seeks to conceal criminal property. The Money Laundering Regulations 2007 (MLRs) focus on ensuring regulated businesses put in place controls to guard against money laundering or terrorist finance. Supervisors are appointed by the Treasury to monitor compliance with these regulations and primarily use a range of supervisory tools to promote compliance, including warning notices, action plans, financial penalties or withdrawal of the right to practice. The vast majority of breaches of the MLRs are remedied or penalised using these supervisory tools. Since 2010, 10 people have been successfully convicted for breaching the Regulations.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-09T14:56:17.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760817/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760817/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Money Laundering: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many successful prosecutions there have been for offences under the Money Laundering Regulations 2007 in each year from 2010.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760818","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-12","<p>Defra is undertaking a cost benefit analysis of the introduction of separate food waste collections that will assess the impact on local government and landfill tax.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-12T11:34:06.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760818/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760818/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-14","Food: Waste Disposal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if his Department will undertake a cost-benefit analysis of the introduction of mandatory separate food waste collections in England, including the effect on (a) local government and (b) landfill tax receipts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","105402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760819","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The information requested on the number of private hospitals registered as charities is not available. Charities and tax relief data held by HM Revenue and Customs cannot be broken down into such sector specific detail.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T15:01:57.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760819/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760819/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Hospitals: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many private hospitals are registered as charities; and if he will make an estimate of the savings in tax payable to those hospitals as a result of being that status.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","105320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760820","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-09","<p>The delivery of the new Customs Declaration Service is on target, and HM Revenue and Customs expects to meet its planned delivery date in January 2019. The progress of the programme is subject to rigorous and ongoing internal scrutiny.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-09T14:59:54.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760820/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760820/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress has been made on the introduction of the new Customs Declaration Service; when he plans for that service to be fully functional; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","105319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760821","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The business rate liability for individual NHS Trusts is based, as with other non-domestic properties, on the rateable value of the property or properties they occupy, as assessed by the independent Valuation Office Agency.</p><p>A private hospital which is a charity and using their property wholly or mainly for charitable purposes may be entitled to 80 per cent rate relief in the normal way, as with all other eligible charities. Charities in the healthcare sector make an important contribution to our society and it is right they should benefit from rate relief.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-09T10:28:00.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760821/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760821/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Hospitals: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to ensure that NHS trusts pay an equivalent level of business rates to private hospitals.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","105318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760822","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The quoted Eurobond exemption is a longstanding exemption which enables UK companies to access investment capital from foreign markets and reduces frictions in financial markets. In response to concerns about the use of interest payments to shift taxable profits overseas, the Government has recently introduced a restriction on the deductibility of corporate interest expense. The rules ensure that companies cannot use excess deductions for interest expense to reduce their taxable profits and erode the UK tax base. This is forecast to raise approx. £1bn per annum.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-12T16:20:53.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760822/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760822/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Stocks and Shares: Channel Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals (a) to amend section 841 of the UK Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988 to withdraw recognition of the securities issued at the Channel Islands Stock Exchange and (b) under which UK companies would be required to withhold 20 per cent from the payment of interest to all Jersey-based companies and remit that sum to HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760823","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government is committed to tackling tax avoidance and evasion at all levels to ensure everyone, no matter who they are, pays the right amount of tax at the right time. Last year, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMRC" target="_blank">HMRC</a> brought in a record additional £29 billion by cracking down on avoidance, evasion and non-compliance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is legislating for over ten measures in the current Finance Bill to further crackdown on those who try to avoid or evade paying the tax that is owed. This includes a penalty for those who enable the use of tax avoidance schemes that are later defeated by HMRC – which builds on the action which has already been taken in tackling marketed avoidance.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-12T16:18:59.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760823/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760823/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","British Home Stores: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will commission an independent inquiry into tax avoidance schemes used by BHS.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","105245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760824","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is aware of the change in the Valuation Office Agency’s approach to assessing units within buildings of multiple occupation, which follows the Supreme Court judgement in the Mazars v Woolway case. The Government is considering the implications of this judgement. Following Budget 2016, the Government announced a wide-ranging package of measures to support rate payers, that will be worth £9 billion over the next five years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","105341 ; 105346","2017-10-09T10:05:26.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760824/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760824/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to mitigate any detriment for businesses arising from the judgment in the Mazars v Woolway case.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Bailey","West Bromwich West","Mr Adrian Bailey","105340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760825","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is aware of the change in the Valuation Office Agency’s approach to assessing units within buildings of multiple occupation, which follows the Supreme Court judgement in the Mazars v Woolway case. The Government is considering the implications of this judgement. Following Budget 2016, the Government announced a wide-ranging package of measures to support rate payers, that will be worth £9 billion over the next five years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","105340 ; 105346","2017-10-09T10:05:26.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760825/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760825/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he or officials of his Department have raised concerns with (a) HM Revenue and Customs or (b) the Valuation Office Agency on the potential effects for businesses of the judgment in the Mazars v Woolway case.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Bailey","West Bromwich West","Mr Adrian Bailey","105341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760826","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is aware of the change in the Valuation Office Agency’s approach to assessing units within buildings of multiple occupation, which follows the Supreme Court judgement in the Mazars v Woolway case. The Government is considering the implications of this judgement. Following Budget 2016, the Government announced a wide-ranging package of measures to support rate payers, that will be worth £9 billion over the next five years.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","105340 ; 105341","2017-10-09T10:05:26.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760826/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760826/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research his Department has commissioned into the (a) effects on businesses of the judgment in the Mazars v Woolway case and (b) options which exist to prevent such negative effects.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","105346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760827","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>Time spent in temporary accommodation ensures no family is without a roof over their head. The Government is assisting areas to ensure that families spend no longer than 6 weeks in B&amp;Bs, which includes protecting and maintaining the homelessness prevention funding at £315 million. We have also replaced Department of Work and Pension’s Temporary Accommodation Management Fee with a Flexible Homelessness Support Grant which local authorities can use more strategically to prevent and tackle homelessness. This amounts to £402 million over the two years from 2017/18.</p><p>While the number of households in temporary accommodation is below the 2004 peak, the law is clear that households with dependent children should only be accommodated in B&amp;B in an emergency and for no longer than six weeks, which commences when the household moves in.</p><p>When a family is accommodated in a B&amp;B, the local authority must provide written information that the period of accommodation should be no more than 6 weeks, after which the authority must secure alternative suitable accommodation. Under the law, any accommodation must be suitable.</p><p>A small number of authorities (around 5 per cent) account for 80 per cent of breaches. The Government has been clear that in normal circumstances the long term use of B&amp;B accommodation for families with children is both inappropriate and unlawful and we are determined to stop this practice. There are councils who are successfully reducing the number and length of time families are spending in B&amp;B accommodation and we expect areas in similar situations to follow their example.</p><p>The Local Government and Social Care Ombudsman publishes guidance on remedying personal injustice where one of their investigations reveals there has been fault, including investigations in relation to Homelessness. The Local Government and Social Care Ombudsman publishes all decisions on complaints on their website, including any remedies they recommend.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","105185 ; 105186 ; 105243","2017-10-09T11:41:29.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760827/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760827/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Bed and Breakfast Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 45358, on the Government's response to the UN Committee on the Rights of the Child, what progress his Department has made on the implementation of the recommendation that it should strictly implement that homeless families should spend no longer than six weeks in bed and breakfast accommodation.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","105326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760828","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government is committed to preventing and tackling homelessness, and no one should ever have to spend a night on the streets.</p><p>I confirmed in January 2017 that the Government would fund the Homelessness Reduction Act in line with the longstanding 'new burdens' arrangement and provide £61 million to local authorities to meet the new burdens cost of the Act.</p><p>The distribution formula is being finalised following consultation with local authorities from across the country, and we plan to announce allocations in the autumn and make the first payments in winter 2017/2018.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-09T10:10:22.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760828/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760828/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish the criteria to be used for the allocation of the £61 million New Burdens fund available to local authorities to implement the Homelessness Reduction Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","105325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760829","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) launched the Let Property Campaign in 2013, which focusses on the residential property letting market. It aims to help landlords to get their tax right from day one, keeping them on track and offering an opportunity to address previous errors. The campaign has been successful at both providing education material to prevent tax loss and enabling landlords to bring their affairs up to date.</p><p>The Let Property Campaign has raised over £115m in additional tax, interest and penalties to December 2016. Of that total, £9.6m represents penalties paid by landlords.</p><p>HMRC plan to continue the Let Property Campaign for the foreseeable future as it continues to help ensure customers understand their obligation and to target those that choose not to meet them.</p><p>HMRC does not hold information in a form that allows them to provide the estimate requested. However, data sources used in the Let Property Campaign include information annually requested from local authorities: a register of all licenses issued for Homes with Multiple Occupancy, and local authority returns of Housing Benefit paid directly to Landlords during the last financial year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","105115 ; 105117","2017-10-12T16:07:33.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760829/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760829/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-14","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the additional (a) tax revenue and (b) revenue derived from penalties that resulted from local authorities sharing data with HMRC.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","105419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760830","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-13","<p>Following the Chancellor’s announcement of the Business Rates Relief Schemes at the Budget, on 9 March the Department published a Business Rates Information Letter to local authorities. This provided information on each of the three schemes including draft allocations for the discretionary relief scheme and guidance on the Supporting Small Business Scheme. On 10 March the Department began discussions with a group of local authorities and the main software suppliers to discuss the implementation of the schemes and system requirements.</p><p>The Department has continued to engage local authorities and software suppliers, encouraging authorities to speed up implementation and publishing the technical guidance for the Supporting Small Business Scheme and Pubs Relief Scheme on 20 June. However, local authorities have overall responsibility for awarding and maintaining contracts with their software providers and for ensuring value for money. While authorities have been able to manually identify eligible businesses for the Supporting Small Business Scheme since March, some authorities chose to wait for a full software update that enabled them to automate this process.</p><p>I met software providers on 12 July and agreed that the software update would be provided to authorities by 21 August at the latest. The update was released by all of the main software providers by this date. On 14 September I made a Written Ministerial Statement, which set out the good progress made by some authorities and a commitment to publish a list of authorities that have rebilled across all three schemes. This has now been published and is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-rates-relief-schemes-2017-rebilling-progress" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-rates-relief-schemes-2017-rebilling-progress</a></p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-13T12:48:26.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760830/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760830/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department made an assessment of the effect on the timescale for local authorities to grant business rate reliefs detailed in Budget 2017 of the readiness of software used by local authorities in advance of making that commitment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","105413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760831","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Housing and Planning Act 2016 and Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017 contain a package of measures to make the compulsory purchase system clearer, fairer and faster for all. These important reforms are being implemented on a staged basis: on 22 September we commenced a number of provisions in the Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017, and the Government will now take forward work on the outstanding measures.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","105331","2017-10-09T10:17:45.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760831/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760831/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Compulsory Purchase: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to implement clauses 195 and 196 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 and clauses 38 and 39 of the Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","105330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760832","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Housing and Planning Act 2016 and Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017 contain a package of measures to make the compulsory purchase system clearer, fairer and faster for all. These important reforms are being implemented on a staged basis: on 22 September we commenced a number of provisions in the Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017, and the Government will now take forward work on the outstanding measures.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","105330","2017-10-09T10:17:44.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760832/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760832/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-14","Compulsory Purchase: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reason he is yet to implement clauses 195 and 196 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 and clauses 38 and 39 of the Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","105331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760833","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>I continue to be kept regularly updated on this matter. Talks around where the club will be playing its home matches from next season are still ongoing. I would urge Coventry City FC and the other relevant parties to agree a plan, so that attention can turn to working together, to provide the clarity needed for the club and its loyal supporters.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-09T11:07:45.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760833/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760833/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Coventry City Football Club","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the hon. Member for Daventry on the mediation process relating to Coventry City Football Club; and what progress has been made to date during that process.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","105424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760834","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-11","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) provides and regularly updates guidance for a wide range of public and private sector organisations, including in the critical national infrastructure. The guidance encourages organisations to understand and design their systems to be resilient to a range of common attacks, including Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks.</p><p><br>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport is considering the need for the right incentives to be in place to build security into internet-connected products and services. This will help protect devices from being hijacked or misused as part of a DDoS attack. The NCSC’s Active Cyber Defence programme is a mechanism through which it is working with the Internet Service Provider community in order to make DDoS attacks harder systemically.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-11T14:26:28.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760834/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760834/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to improve public and private sector organisations' protection against distributed denial of service attacks.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760835","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Cyber Essentials scheme is intended to provide a minimum level of good, basic cyber security for any organisation, of any size, in any sector. It sets out the measures which any organisation can implement itself to protect against the most common Internet threats. Distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks are difficult to protect against in the same way. Including DDoS mitigation within Cyber Essentials would significantly raise the bar assessed by the scheme, adding significant cost to organisations, even if they were unlikely to ever be the subject of such an attack.</p><p> </p><p>Organisations requiring protection from DDoS can consult guidance provided by the National Cyber Security Centre. They can also seek help from third parties offering these services (e.g. Internet Service Providers.)</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-11T14:21:37.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760835/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760835/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the mitigation of distributed denial of service attacks is not included in the Government's cyber essentials scheme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760836","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-11","<p>The National Cyber Security Centre provides and regularly updates guidance for a range of public and private sector organisations, including in the critical national infrastructure (CNI). The guidance encourages organisations to understand and design their systems to be resilient to a range of common attacks, including Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks. The NCSC’s Active Cyber Defence programme is a mechanism through which it is working with the Internet Service Provider community in order to make DDoS attacks harder systemically.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is working closely with CNI operators to ensure they are adequately protected from cyber threats, including DDoS attacks. The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) is currently consulting on the proposed implementation of the EU Network and Information Systems (NIS) Directive. This Directive will place a legal obligation on operators of essential services to ensure they have appropriate security measures in place to deal with cyber threats. DCMS is also considering the need for the right incentives to be in place to build security into internet-connected products and services. This will help protect devices from being hijacked or misused as part of a DDoS attack.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-11T14:24:34.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760836/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760836/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Cybercrime: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to protect critical national infrastructure from distributed denial of service attacks.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","105255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760837","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Sport England is working with the Football Association on a new programme of support for grassroots football. Details of the new funding award for the period 2017-2021 and how this will align with the objectives set out in the government's sport strategy Sporting Future and Sport England's strategy Towards an Active Nation will be announced shortly.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-09T11:10:32.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760837/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760837/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the Football Association on catalysing grass roots football.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","105257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760838","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Government announced a review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures in 2016 to ensure that we have the right balance between a sector that can grow and contribute to the economy, and one that is socially responsible and doing all it can to protect consumers and wider communities. We hope to publish the findings of the review by October at the earliest.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-09T11:12:23.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760838/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760838/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of giving additional powers to local authorities to review, amend and revoke betting premises' licences for establishments with fixed-odds betting terminals which those authorities consider to be detrimental to their local communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Seely","Isle of Wight","Mr Bob Seely","105388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760839","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Football Association has responsibility for the regulation of intermediaries in the game. Their role includes proper investigation of any evidence of inappropriate behaviour. The integrity of sport is absolutely paramount, and the UK Sports Governance code, which the FA has signed up to, sets out clearly what we expect in terms of the highest standards of governance and transparency from all our sports governing bodies.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-09T11:17:04.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760839/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760839/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Football: Commercial Agents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will commission a review of the role, responsibilities and financial compliance of football agents.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","105258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760840","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-10","<p>Catfishing is one of the online harms which we are considering as part of our Internet Safety Strategy. The Strategy is due to be published shortly and we will consider ways in which we can ensure Britain is the safest place in the world to be online.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-10T11:44:58.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760840/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760840/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-14","Personation: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had on measures to deal with catfishing in the Internet Safety Strategy.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","105382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760841","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-10","<p>The number of recruits to the Royal Welsh regiment and Welsh Guards regiment who were resident in Wales in each of the last four years is shown in the table below. Data prior to 2013-14 is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p> </p></td><td colspan="4"><p>Financial Year</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Welsh Guards regiment</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Welsh regiment</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>80</p></td><td><p>70</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Data is a single service estimate and not official statistics.</p><p>Data is based on recruits who were assigned to a Phase 1 training course and expressed a first preference for the relevant infantry regiment.</p><p>Data is based upon recruit postcode being affiliated with one of the Army Careers Centres in Wales.</p><p>Figures have been rounded to the nearest 10.</p><p>Rounding is necessary, as a means of disclosure control and the preservation of anonymity.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","105384","2017-10-10T14:44:34.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760841/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760841/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-14","Royal Welsh: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many recruits to the Royal Welsh regiment were resident in Wales in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","105383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760842","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not make an assessment of the number of civilian casualties as a result of Saudi Arabian air strikes as we do not have access to all the information that would allow us to do so accurately.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-11T15:40:12.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760842/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/760842/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-14","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the number of civilian casualties killed in Saudi Arabian air strikes in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","105302"
